To identify the structures and functional groups of N-CDs, FT-IR (Fig. 2
                        ) and XPS (Fig. 3
                        ) were performed. According to the analysis in Fig. 2, the stretching vibration of NH is near 3379 cm−1 and a secondary amine, the stretching vibration of OH is near 3210 cm−1, and the stretching vibration of CH is about 2880 cm−1. The CC bond stretching vibrations of aromatic hydrocarbons near 1460, 1520, 1578 and 1638 cm−1 indicate that they contain a benzene ring structure. The characteristic absorption peak of –CH3 is around 1350 cm−1, the peak around 1240 cm−1 indicates the presence of C-OH, and the strong peak at 1097 cm−1 is COC. Below 1000 cm−1 is the position of bending vibration of aromatic ring substituents.

Table 1
 shows the comparison between the proposed sensor and other fluorescence probes for the determination of Cu2+. The results show that the proposed sensor exhibits a wider linear range. The CIE map (Fig. 7
) further confirms the fluorescence color of N-CDs, which is consistent with the emission fluorescence spectrum shown in Fig. 4a.

Before and after adding Cu2+, the lifetimes of the two showed extremely high consistency, 2.29 ns and 2.21 ns, respectively (Fig. 9
                        a). Therefore, we preliminarily judged that the detection mechanism of the N-CDs to Cu2+ is static quenching effect. Next, we investigated the effect of different concentrations of Cu2+ on the UV absorption spectra of N-CDs (Fig. 9b). With the increase of Cu2+ concentration (85–140 μmol/L), the absorption band of the tested system changed. Subsequently, we measured the Zata potential of N-CDs and N-CDs/Cu2+, respectively. After adding Cu2+, the Zata potential value of N-CDs solution increased from 1.67 mV to 3.34 mV (Fig. 10
                        ). This further confirms that the mechanism of their interaction may be that Cu2+ complexes with N-CDs to produce new substances. As can be seen from Fig. 8a, black complexes were formed after the addition of Cu2+, which quenched the fluorescence. In Fig. 6b, when the concentration of Cu2+ is 0–30 µM, the reaction rate is slow and the fluorescence intensity decreases little. In the range of 30–80 µM, the reaction rate increases and the fluorescence intensity decreases significantly. In the range of 80–140 µM, Cu2+ is saturated, the reaction is complete, and the fluorescence is basically quenched. In addition, UV absorption spectra by using high concentration CDs plus copper ion were obtained (Fig. S1). It can be seen that the addition of copper ions causes some obvious changes in the UV absorptions of the CDs solution, which provides certain evidence for the mechanism of static quenching.

First, we selected HeLa cells to evaluate the toxicity of N-CDs using the MTT standard method. When the N-CDs concentration reaches 160 μg/mL, 89.05 % of HeLa cells survive after 24 h of incubation (Fig. 11
                        ). This means that the N-CDs have low toxicity and can be used for biomarkers and cell imaging. As shown in Fig. 12
                        , HeLa cells stained with N-CDs show bright red fluorescence, and it was found that N-CDs could not only enter the cytoplasm, but also enter the nucleus. In addition, based on the analysis and detection of Cu2+ by N-CDs, Cu2+ was added to the above-mentioned HeLa cell culture dish stained with N-CDs, and it was observed that the fluorescence intensity in the cells decreased immediately after the addition of Cu2+. The results that the prepared N-CDs can be used as a visual sensing platform to track the fluctuations of Cu2+ in living cells.

We further added the N-CDs to zebrafish larvae to study their utility in vivo. First, we conducted a zebrafish toxicity experiment. The experimental results showed that 90 % zebrafish had strong activity when the concentration of N-CDs reached 0.4 mg/mL for 3 h (Fig. 13
                        ). It shows that the N-CDs have good biocompatibility. On this basis, we carried out in vivo imaging of zebrafish. Zebrafish larvae labeled with N-CDs (1.11 mg/mL) could clearly be seen a bright red fluorescence signal (Fig. 14
                        ). Interestingly, after the introduction of Cu2+ (1 mM), the fluorescence intensity of zebrafish larvae labeled with N-CDs significantly decreased, indicating that the obtained N-CDs can be successfully used to monitor Cu2+ in vivo.
